<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11153a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11153a">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11153a"> 153(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Constance &mdash; Caesar</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[<b>Bataille des Romains et des Francs</b>]</font> <mark>Constance</mark>, qui, du milieu du corps de r&eacute;serve, suivait de l&apos;oeil les mouvements des troupes, aper&ccedil;oit le d&eacute;couragement des cohortes. Il se tourne vers la l&eacute;gion chr&eacute;tienne: &ldquo;Braves soldats, la fortune de Rome est entre vos mains. Marchons &agrave; l&apos;ennemi!&rdquo; / Aussit&ocirc;t les fid&egrave;les abaissent devant <mark>C&eacute;sar</mark> leurs aigles, surmont&eacute;es de l&apos;&eacute;tendard du salut. <br><font color="green">[Constantius who, from amid the reserve corps, did not lose sight of the moves of his troops, perceived discouragement among the cohorts. He turned to the Christian legion: &ldquo;Soldiers, brave men, the fortune of Rome is in your hands. Let us for the enemy!&rdquo; Directly the faithful lowered before Caesar their eagles surmounted by the Saviour&apos;s pennon.]</font> <small> Chateaubriand, <a name="CHBD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHBD"><cite title="source">&OElig;uvres choisies illustr&eacute;es</cite></a> (1912) II, <cite>Les Martyrs</cite> 64</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
